Mining Madness!

by: Jayden Kudo

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game because there was a minigame that inspired me on roblox to make this. My decision to make this game was that other games seemed a little too basic and not a lot to it. Also, I wanted to get a lot of the code from the league invaders game since there was a lot of new stuff that I learned.

2. What I Learned

Some feedback that a tester gave me was that I should add lives. Since I wasn't really sure how to add them, he tought me on how to add them and it was quite easy in the end. Also, he wanted me to make the objects fall slower and the screen to be bigger, and the rest is history!

3. Architecture of My Game

My game shows a roblox noob character and a pickaxe next to him. The character was to make it more realistic. The pickaxe will mine the crystals and bombs. If it hits the bomb, you lose a life but if you hit a crystal, you gain a point. The objects class helps to make a backbone for all of the objects just in one class. The ObjectManager class is to help manage on object spawning, what happens to them on each event, etc. Game panel is to show the game state, menu and end state and controls the frame rate, and much more!

4. Technical Implementation

The aspect I feel most proud of is the timer, score and lives tracker. How I accomplished my goal was to look at my league invaders project, extract some code from it that I had learned, and add some of my own functions such as adding 2 types of objects with 2 different functions during a pickaxe collision and making one of each of them randomly fall in different places in a vertical motion, and then added time left, lives and total points in the upper lefthand corner.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of this project was trying to figure out on how I could add in time left. Some of the difficulties I faced were using the wait method, which apparently doesn't function correctly and using the java date object and getting the timer to work correctly. I overcame these difficulties by working with a teacher to make it count down from 85 correctly instead of getting a weird number (e.g. -673727153), making it count down instead of up, and going on to stackOverflow to find the method to get Java's internal clock.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

Some improvements I could make for the future if I ever continue would be adding different levels and/or a virtual currency system. Also, I could make the timer to start counting down when it actually starts.
